Now `hs` is `q = ⟨s p.1, permMapWalk n s p.2⟩`. We can use this to rewrite `q.2` in our goal:

```tactics
  have h1 : q.2 = permMapWalk n s p.2 := by
    exact congrArg Prod.snd hs
```

Now we can rewrite `(edgeSet q.2).card` using `h1`:

```tactics
  rw [h1]
```

So our goal becomes `(edgeSet p.2).card = (edgeSet (permMapWalk n s p.2)).card`.

To prove this, we need to show that applying `permMapWalk n s` to `p.2` results in a loop walk whose edge set has the same cardinality as `p.2`'s edge set. 

The key insight is that `permMapWalk n s` is a bijection on the set of loop walks, and thus preserves the cardinality of their edge sets. Specifically, the edges of the new loop walk are the images of the edges of the original under the permutation `s`.

